Title:
Demonstration of general 2d potentials (minor modification of 2d HO)

# NOTE: implementation is somewhat rough and not all plausible inputs work
#       try the alternatives below to see what works and what not

# Below we define our discretization axis:
Axis: name,nCoefficients,lower end, upper end,functions,order
X1,30,-7,7,polynomial,15
X2,30,-7,7,polynomial,15

# Hamiltonian in the tensor product space L2( dx1 dx2, R^2) = L2(dx1,R) (x) L2(dx2,R)

# Alternative 0: (DVR) -- see explanations below
Operator: hamiltonian
0.5(<d_1_d><1>+<1><d_1_d>)+0.5<{}><X1*X1+X2*X2>

# Alternative 1: exact integral on X1 coordinate
#Operator: hamiltonian
0.5(<d_1_d><1>+<1><d_1_d>)+0.5<{Int}><X1*X1+X2*X2>

# Alternative 2: (separable potential)
#Operator: hamiltonian
0.5(<d_1_d><1>+<1><d_1_d>)+0.5<Q*Q><1>+0.5<1><Q*Q>

# Alternative 3: (hard-coded "class Sum")
#Operator: hamiltonian
0.5(<d_1_d><1>+<1><d_1_d>)+0.5<{Int}><Sum(X1*X1,X2*X2)>


# we will print the lowest eigenvalues and stop
Eigen: select=SmallReal[20]

# Inner workings of the code:
(a) if both coordinates are DVR and the factor on the first is <{}>
    the code will use DVR integration on both (here X1 and X2)
    this makes efficient purely diagonal operators on the X1-X2 plane
    it will only work when both axes are FE-DVR
    (Alternative 0)

(b) if the factor on the first is <{Int}>, more accurate integration
    over first will be forced, even if DVR were possible
    at present, <{Int}> can only be used on single-element functions (not for FE)
    i.e. need to change to
    X1,30,-7,7,polynomial,30
    (Alternative 1)

(c) Of course, if the potential is separabble as in this example, it is
    more efficient to exploit that separability
    (Alternative 2)

(d) There are a few hard-coded 2-argument functions, here class AlgebraSum, which will be more
    efficient in setup than when the expression <{}><X1*X1+X2*X2> must be evaluated
    This can be extended in C++ using the examples
    (Alternative 3)



